<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
5. 
<taxonomicName LSID="5B499517-3CAE-56FE-8454-00959F67BC37" authority="Lazkov, Bot. Zhurn. (Moscow &amp; Leningrad). 84 (9): 123. 1999." family="Caryophyllaceae" genus="S." higherTaxonomySource="treatment-meta" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="S. georgievskyi" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="georgievskyi">S. georgievskyi Lazkov, Bot. Zhurn. (Moscow &amp; Leningrad). 84 (9): 123. 1999.</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="materials_examined">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Type.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
[Syria], Desertum Syriacum. 30 km ad austro-orient. Ab urb. Deir-Ez-Zor, vallis undulata, ass. Ephem.-car. Frequens, 15 May 1985, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">A. Georgievsky s.n.</emphasis>
(Holotype: LE! [LE01051363]).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
20.0-50.0 cm tall, erect. Stem pubescent in lower part, scabrous, pubescent with sessile glands in upper part; with 8-12 distinct internodes, the uppermost internode obviously longer than the next upper internode. Basal leaves linear or oblanceolate, pubescent. Cauline leaves linear 10.0-40.0
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
1.0-3.0 mm, pubescent. Calyx 25.0-30.0 mm long, ovoid at anthesis and clavate in fruit, pubescent; teeth unequal; shorter ones 2.0-4.0 mm, ovate, acuminate; longer ones 4.0-6.0 mm, lanceolate, acuminate; marginal hairs long (longer than 0.5 mm), dense. Inflorescence non-divaricate, branch axile (much) less than 90°. Petal claws 10.0-12.0 mm long, glabrous; limbs 7.0-9.0 mm long, bifid, upper-surface pink, lobes oblong, petal limbs cleft to middle or more; coronal scales 2.0-2.2 mm long. Anthophore 13.0-16.0 mm long, glabrous or puberulent. Anthers exserted; filaments 12.0-15.0 mm long, glabrous. Styles exserted. First pedicel 1.0-4.0 cm in flower, 2.0-6.0 cm in fruit, erect, glabrous, apex antrorse. Capsule 12.0 mm long, oblong or ellipsoid. Seeds 0.8-1.0 mm wide.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Syria, N Iraq (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="F7" captionText="Figure 7. Distribution map of S. sect. Arenosae. Each color code corresponds to one taxon: A S. arenosa B S. austroiranica C S. chaetodonta D S. exsudans E S. georgievskyi F S. leyseroides G S. linearis H S. microsperma subsp. cypria I S. microsperma subsp. maritima J S. microsperma subsp. microsperma K S. microsperma subsp. modesta L S. striata." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.159.51500.figure7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/447291" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">7</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
At the molecular level, we have two sequences for each ITS and 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">rps16</emphasis>
and only one for 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">RPB2</emphasis>
. All the three markers were sequenced for the specimen from Syria (
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. georgievskyi" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="georgievskyi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">S. georgievskyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
ID. 42), but for the specimen from Iraq, the ITS and 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">rps16</emphasis>
regions were sequenced from two duplicate specimens from different herbaria. The two accessions of 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. georgievskyi" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="georgievskyi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">S. georgievskyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from Iraq and Syria do not form a monophyletic group in the species, ITS and 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">rps16</emphasis>
trees (Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Species tree from two STACEY runs and three unlinked regions (ITS, RPB 2, rps 16). Posterior probabilities&gt; 0.75 are shown above branches. The number following the taxonomic name is the specimen ID (Suppl. material 1). Scale bar reﬂects the number of substitutions per site." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.159.51500.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/447285" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">1</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Phylogenetic tree resulting from Bayesian analysis of the ITS sequences including 76 taxa. The trees were summarized in a 50 % majority-rule consensus tree with the posterior probabilities (PP) indicated above branches. Bootstrap support values (&gt; 75 %) based on MP and ML are noted below branches, respectively. The numbers following the taxonomic name indicate the specimen ID and Genbank numbers (Suppl. material 1), respectively." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.159.51500.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/447287" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">3</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Phylogenetic tree resulting from Bayesian analysis of the rps 16 sequences including 71 taxa. The trees were summarized in a 50 % majority-rule consensus tree with the posterior probabilities (PP) indicated above branches. Bootstrap support values (&gt; 75 %) based on MP and ML are noted below branches, respectively. The numbers following the taxonomic name indicate the specimen ID and Genbank numbers (Suppl. material 1), respectively." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.159.51500.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/447288" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">4</figureCitation>
). The accession from Iraq (
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. georgievskyi" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="georgievskyi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">S. georgievskyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
ID. 41) is found together with the accessions of 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. chaetodonta" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="chaetodonta">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">S. chaetodonta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in a moderately to strongly supported clades in the species (PP = 0.78, Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Species tree from two STACEY runs and three unlinked regions (ITS, RPB 2, rps 16). Posterior probabilities&gt; 0.75 are shown above branches. The number following the taxonomic name is the specimen ID (Suppl. material 1). Scale bar reﬂects the number of substitutions per site." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.159.51500.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/447285" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">1</figureCitation>
) and 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">rps16</emphasis>
(PP = 1.00 MPB = 94% MLB = 96%, Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Phylogenetic tree resulting from Bayesian analysis of the rps 16 sequences including 71 taxa. The trees were summarized in a 50 % majority-rule consensus tree with the posterior probabilities (PP) indicated above branches. Bootstrap support values (&gt; 75 %) based on MP and ML are noted below branches, respectively. The numbers following the taxonomic name indicate the specimen ID and Genbank numbers (Suppl. material 1), respectively." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.159.51500.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/447288" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">4</figureCitation>
) trees, respectively. The accession from Syria is nested within a clade including 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. microsperma" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="microsperma">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">S. microsperma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the species tree (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Species tree from two STACEY runs and three unlinked regions (ITS, RPB 2, rps 16). Posterior probabilities&gt; 0.75 are shown above branches. The number following the taxonomic name is the specimen ID (Suppl. material 1). Scale bar reﬂects the number of substitutions per site." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.159.51500.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/447285" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">1</figureCitation>
) and weakly supported in 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">rps16</emphasis>
tree (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Phylogenetic tree resulting from Bayesian analysis of the rps 16 sequences including 71 taxa. The trees were summarized in a 50 % majority-rule consensus tree with the posterior probabilities (PP) indicated above branches. Bootstrap support values (&gt; 75 %) based on MP and ML are noted below branches, respectively. The numbers following the taxonomic name indicate the specimen ID and Genbank numbers (Suppl. material 1), respectively." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.159.51500.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/447288" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">4</figureCitation>
, PP&lt;0.75). In the ITS tree, the accessions of 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. georgievskyi" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="georgievskyi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">S. georgievskyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
do not form a monophyletic group, but they are included in a strongly supported clade together with 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. chaetodonta" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="chaetodonta">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">S. chaetodonta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. striata" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="striata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">S. striata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(PP = 0.98 MPB = 86% MLB = 93%, Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Phylogenetic tree resulting from Bayesian analysis of the ITS sequences including 76 taxa. The trees were summarized in a 50 % majority-rule consensus tree with the posterior probabilities (PP) indicated above branches. Bootstrap support values (&gt; 75 %) based on MP and ML are noted below branches, respectively. The numbers following the taxonomic name indicate the specimen ID and Genbank numbers (Suppl. material 1), respectively." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.159.51500.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/447287" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">3</figureCitation>
). The morphological distinctiveness (much longer calyx, long anthophore and larger petals) speaks in favour of recognition of the species, and although chromosome numbers are unknown, we hypothesize that the incongruent pattern seen in the Syrian specimen may be explained by polyploid hybridization. Allopolyploids often grow larger than their parents (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.tplants.2009.12.003" author="Chen, ZJ" journalOrPublisher="Trends in Plant Science" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="57 - 71" refId="B12" refString="Chen, ZJ, 2010. Molecular mechanisms of polyploidy and hybrid vigor. Trends in Plant Science 15 (2): 57 - 71, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1016/j.tplants.2009.12.003" title="Molecular mechanisms of polyploidy and hybrid vigor." url="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.tplants.2009.12.003" volume="15" year="2010">Chen 2010</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName authorityName="G. A. Lazkov" authorityYear="1999" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Caryophyllaceae" genus="Silene" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Silene georgievskyi" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="georgievskyi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Silene georgievskyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is morphologically larger in floral and general habit aspects compared to both 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. chaetodonta" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="chaetodonta">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">S. chaetodonta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. microsperma" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="microsperma">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">S. microsperma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. There may be a small overlap in the distributions of 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. chaetodonta" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="chaetodonta">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">S. chaetodonta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. georgievskyi" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="georgievskyi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">S. georgievskyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, in the border area between Iraq and Syria.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
